[Student "W"]
{The bidding has been as shown. The contract is 3NT 

Lead the \SQ, the top of a broken honor sequence.

The top of a solid 3-card honor sequence is best, but as you can see, a broken 3-card sequence may work out just as good.

North will likely try the \C finesse, and when West wins the \CK he will return a \S through North's \ST.}
[Play "W"]SQ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:AQT6.7.KJ962.K65 943.964.AQT8.983 KJ72.KJT32.7.A74 85.AQ85.543.QJT2"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4S"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1D pass 1H pass 1S pass 4S pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "b742afe2826b9ac67b677a11acb56a20c7efcf62a4b6110076822704f9899f9e"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "defense/opening_leads"]
[Student "W"]
{The bidding has been as shown. The contract is 4\S 

Lead any \S.

You have \D winners, but dummy will surely be short since he has at least 8 cards in the Major suits.

Partner has whatever \H strength your side possesses.

It is very likely that declarer will want to do some cross-trumping. To try to cut that down your best lead is a trump.

Just imagine that declarer wins the first \S in his hand and plays a \H to dummy's honors. North will win and play another trump. Whenever you win your first \D you will play your last trump.

As you can imagine, declarer will be in a whole lot of trouble.}

